You already hold a shared BlobContainerClient DATA_CONTAINER that points to data. Perfect. From here, keep everything under that one container and treat the rest as virtual folders (just blob names with slashes).

Here’s a clean, production‑style way to proceed.

1) Path & tagging helpers (tiny, reusable)

package com.neo.notification.blob;

import java.net.URLEncoder;
import java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;
import java.time.OffsetDateTime;
import java.time.format.DateTimeFormatter;

public final class BlobPaths {
    private static final DateTimeFormatter TS = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("yyyyMMddHHmmss");

    private BlobPaths() {}

    /** Ensure docId is path‑safe */
    public static String safe(String s) {
        return URLEncoder.encode(s, StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
    }

    /** e.g. container1/abc%2F123/ */
    public static String folder(String logicalContainer, String docId) {
        return safe(logicalContainer) + "/" + safe(docId) + "/";
    }

    /** Baseline name: e.g. container1/abc/id.json */
    public static String baseline(String logicalContainer, String docId) {
        return folder(logicalContainer, docId) + safe(docId) + ".json";
    }

    /** Version name: e.g. container1/abc/id-20250730T084512.json */
    public static String version(String logicalContainer, String docId, OffsetDateTime when) {
        return folder(logicalContainer, docId) + safe(docId) + "-" + TS.format(when) + ".json";
    }

    /** Tag query to locate “latest” for this doc */
    public static String latestTagQuery(String logicalContainer, String docId) {
        // Tags are strings; keep values simple (no quotes inside).
        return "@docId = '" + safe(docId) + "' AND @container = '" + safe(logicalContainer) + "' AND @latest = 'true'";
    }
}

2) Read “old snapshot” (latest via tags → fallback baseline)

Pass in your shared DATA_CONTAINER and the logical Cosmos container name for this trigger.

package com.neo.notification.change;

import com.azure.core.util.IterableStream;
import com.azure.storage.blob.BlobClient;
import com.azure.storage.blob.BlobContainerClient;
import com.azure.storage.blob.models.TaggedBlobItem;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.node.ObjectNode;

import java.io.ByteArrayOutputStream;
import java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.logging.Logger;

import static com.neo.notification.blob.BlobPaths.*;

public final class OldSnapshotReader {
    private static final ObjectMapper MAPPER = new ObjectMapper();

    private OldSnapshotReader() {}

    /**
     * Load the previous (old) content to compare against.
     * 1) Try index tags (latest=true) under the same DATA container.
     * 2) Fallback to the baseline blob (first-time case).
     * Returns null if not found.
     */
    public static ObjectNode loadOld(
            BlobContainerClient dataContainer,
            String logicalContainer,
            String docId,
            Logger log) {

        // 1) Try latest via tags (search limited to the “data” container)
        String query = latestTagQuery(logicalContainer, docId);
        IterableStream<TaggedBlobItem> hits = dataContainer.findBlobsByTags(query);

        TaggedBlobItem hit = hits.stream().findFirst().orElse(null);
        if (hit != null) {
            BlobClient latest = dataContainer.getBlobClient(hit.getName());
            return readJson(latest, log);
        }

        // 2) Fallback to baseline
        BlobClient baseline = dataContainer.getBlobClient(baseline(logicalContainer, docId));
        if (baseline.exists()) {
            return readJson(baseline, log);
        }

        // Not found (truly first ever)
        return null;
    }

    private static ObjectNode readJson(BlobClient blob, Logger log) {
        try (ByteArrayOutputStream out = new ByteArrayOutputStream()) {
            blob.download(out);
            String json = out.toString(StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
            return (ObjectNode) MAPPER.readTree(json);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            log.severe("Failed to read blob '" + blob.getBlobName() + "': " + e.getMessage());
            return null;
        }
    }
}

3) How to call it from your Function trigger

You already created and share:

private static final BlobContainerClient DATA_CONTAINER =
    BlobClientProvider.container(System.getenv("Blob_ContainerName_Data"));

In the trigger method:

String logicalContainer = System.getenv("ContainerNameToTrack_1");  // the Cosmos container this function watches
String docId = newDoc.get("id").asText();

ObjectNode oldDoc = OldSnapshotReader.loadOld(DATA_CONTAINER, logicalContainer, docId, context.getLogger());
/*
 oldDoc == null:
   - truly first time (no baseline yet), OR
   - baseline missing: choose your policy (e.g., treat as “no change” and create baseline).
 Otherwise:
   - compare oldDoc vs newDoc for your tracked fields.
*/

4) Next steps (quick)
	•	After comparing, write a new version blob (e.g., version(...)) and update tags on the previous “latest” to false, then set tags on the new “latest” to true (@docId, @container, @latest=true).
	•	Use ETag conditional headers on updates to avoid collisions. You already have the shared DATA_CONTAINER, so no new clients are needed.

This keeps your “one DATA container, many virtual folders” design, lets you handle “first time vs later” cleanly, and scales well.